posts.caption:
How do you start your very first Data science project? 📈⠀
⠀
☑ Pick your data⠀
⠀
There are thousands, if not millions, of data sets on the web. Find a data set that interests you about a topic you are passionate about. I have an aggregated list of data repositories you can explore (link in my bio)⠀
⠀
☑ Conduct an Exploratory Data Analysis(EDA)⠀
⠀
Once you have your data set, load it up into Python/R/whatever and start exploring. What relationships exist within your data? What variables are of interest to you? Is there an outcome variable you would like to predict? What are some tools you might want to use to extract insights from your data? ⠀
⠀
☑ Ask questions⠀
⠀
Based on the results of your EDA, what might be some business relevant questions you could answer in an analysis? What insights would you want to gain to help make business decisions using this data? ⠀
⠀
Pro Tip: It's always a good idea to ask general questions first and as you get more familiar with your data, update those initial questions into more precise questions.⠀
⠀
☑ Get to work⠀
⠀
Start researching and coding solutions to the questions you are interested in solving. Feel free to ask more questions as new insights reveal themselves to you in your analysis. Let your curiosity and intuition drive you.⠀
⠀
☑ Create a final report of your findings⠀
⠀
Once you feel like you've answered your questions to the best of your abilities, it's time to communicate your findings into a nice final report. Be sure to include visualizations you made, any statistical tests you used, the models you created as well as the final results of your analysis. It's also worth including how your project could be improved in the future and what additional resources might be helpful.⠀
⠀
Don't worry about being perfect with your first project. No one's going to see it. Just get into the routine of building projects from start to finish. As you do more and more projects, you'll analytical skills and confidence levels will skyrocket🚀⠀
⠀
Did I miss anything? What else would you advise to someone making their very first Data Science project?

posts.caption:
🧠 𝐇𝐨𝐰 𝐭𝐨 𝐠𝐞𝐭 𝐬𝐭𝐚𝐫𝐭𝐞𝐝 𝐚𝐬 𝐰𝐞𝐛 𝐝𝐞𝐬𝐢𝐠𝐧𝐞𝐫 ?

𝟏. 𝐖𝐞𝐛 𝐃𝐞𝐬𝐢𝐠𝐧 𝐓𝐡𝐞𝐨𝐫𝐲

The first knowledge you must have is how to structure the website in a way that is easily understood and navigated. To know all these aspects, you should get yourself well prepared in the knowledge of UX design, which enables you to present the product accurately and lets you know about the information architecture.
𝟐. 𝐊𝐧𝐨𝐰𝐥𝐞𝐝𝐠𝐞 𝐨𝐟 𝐏𝐫𝐨𝐠𝐫𝐚𝐦𝐦𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐋𝐚𝐧𝐠𝐮𝐚𝐠𝐞

Websites are designed and written with some languages of their own. The two of the most used are HTML and CSS. Additionally, it is useful to know JavaScript.
𝟑. 𝐓𝐡𝐫𝐞𝐞 𝐓𝐡𝐢𝐧𝐠𝐬 𝐘𝐨𝐮 𝐍𝐞𝐞𝐝 𝐭𝐨 𝐊𝐧𝐨𝐰

A. Graphic Design : You must know the basics of image editing using Photoshop and open source software Gimp.

B. Using Prototypes : You need to make the prototypes of your web design before you can make the final version, it help you to know how the contents will be presented.
C. Content Management System : You can use this programming languages with a good code editor like Atom or Zoomla. So it would be best if you were well versed in these editors usage. Content management systems like WordPress help you to create websites of almost all types.
𝟒. 𝐓𝐞𝐬𝐭 𝐲𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐖𝐞𝐛𝐬𝐢𝐭𝐞𝐬

It should load quickly in web browsers and be visible properly in both desktops and mobiles. For this, you must test your sites for web browsers regularly.
𝟓. 𝐅𝐚𝐦𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐚𝐫𝐢𝐬𝐞 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐧𝐞𝐰 𝐓𝐫𝐞𝐧𝐝𝐬

New techniques and trends are always flooding the market, and before you know it, a particular trend may become the market leader. So, it would help if you familiarized very regularly what new trends.
𝟔. 𝐖𝐞𝐛 𝐃𝐞𝐬𝐢𝐠𝐧 𝐂𝐨𝐦𝐦𝐮𝐧𝐢𝐭𝐢𝐞𝐬

One of the essential parts of how to become the best web site designers is to mingle and discuss with people in the web designer community.
𝟕. 𝐂𝐫𝐞𝐚𝐭𝐞 𝐚 𝐠𝐨𝐨𝐝 𝐏𝐨𝐫𝐭𝐟𝐨𝐥𝐢𝐨

To present yourself you must create outstanding examples of your work, which you can show your potential to the employers and customers. Use all your creativity to produce excellent websites adding something personal uniqueness to it.

posts.caption:
Day{ 78 ... 84 /300}[EN] #300daysofcode
🧠 Steve Wozniak once said, ( “If you love what you do and are willing to do what it takes, it's within your reach. And it'll be worth every minute you spend alone at night, thinking and thinking about what it is you want to design or build. It'll be worth it, I promise.”)
.
coding is not all the time looking happy. It is actually looking like this and thinking: why the hell my doesn’t my code work? Where does this bug come from now? Why is my code behaving weird?! How do I make it now? And a lot of other questions.
We are always smiling for the picture but the reality is not always that.
.
We all have problems, difficulties and moments of doubt. And it is all ok! Because people who code are people who solve problems and overcome their doubts! Our best friends are Google, Stackoverflow, Dev Tools, console.log and background-color: balck 🤪🤪 In the end, we are able to build great things!
How do you deal with your problems while coding? Do you have a lot of these moments or not so much? What is your experience with this all?
